1.1 Cron formats and field definitions (POSIX/vixie cron)
- Standard crontab expression: five space-separated fields: minute hour day-of-month month day-of-week
- Field order and ranges:
  minute: 0-59
  hour: 0-23
  day-of-month (DOM): 1-31
  month: 1-12 or JAN-DEC
  day-of-week (DOW): 0-7 or SUN-SAT (0 and 7 both Sunday)
- Field separators: white-space (single space recommended). Tabs allowed by implementations but normalize to single spaces before parsing.
- Allowed tokens within a field: * (any), a-b (range inclusive), a,b (list), */n or a-b/n (step values), names for month/day-of-week (JAN, FEB, MON, TUE, etc).

1.2 Quartz Cron format and extensions
- Quartz cron expression: seven fields (seconds minutes hours day-of-month month day-of-week year) where year is optional.
- Field ranges:
  seconds: 0-59
  minutes: 0-59
  hours: 0-23
  day-of-month: 1-31
  month: 1-12 or JAN-DEC
  day-of-week: 1-7 or SUN-SAT (Quartz uses 1=SUN, 2=MON, ... 7=SAT)
  year: optional, e.g., 1970-2099
- Quartz-specific special characters:
  ? : no specific value (used for either DOM or DOW when the other is specified)
  L : last day of the month or last weekday when used with W (e.g., LW)
  W : nearest weekday to given day-of-month (e.g., 15W)
  # : nth day-of-week in the month (e.g., 2#1 = first Monday)
  C : calendar day? (implementation-specific; treat as advanced extension)
- Quartz requires that either DOM or DOW be ? when you need the other to drive scheduling; do not rely on OR semantics used by some cron implementations.

1.3 Special strings and common shorthands
- Common shorthands recognized by many crons: @reboot, @yearly (or @annually), @monthly, @weekly, @daily (or @midnight), @hourly
- Implementation note: shorthands are translated into equivalent cron expressions by the scheduler; store the canonical expression for persistence and comparison.

1.4 Field value grammar: ranges, lists, steps
- Grammar elements and their interpretations:
  * : wildcard matches every permitted value in field range.
  a-b : inclusive range from a to b.
  a,b,c : explicit list containing specified values.
  */n or a-b/n : step values; when used with * means every n units, when used with range means every n units within [a,b].
  Named values: JAN, FEB, MAR... and SUN, MON... are case-insensitive; normalize to upper-case before matching.
- Validation rules: enforce numeric bounds per field; reject values outside permitted ranges; when named values provided, map to their numeric equivalents.

1.5 DOM vs DOW semantics
- POSIX/vixie cron: when both DOM and DOW are restricted (not *), the job runs when either field matches the current time (logical OR). Implementation must replicate this behavior if targeting vixie cron compatibility.
- Quartz: DOM and DOW fields are mutually exclusive selection fields; use ? to indicate the unused field. Do not apply OR semantics for Quartz expressions.
- When offering a parser API, provide explicit mode flags: mode: "cron" (5-field OR semantics) vs "quartz" (7-field, ? semantics) and a strictMode or compatibility flag to reject ambiguous expressions.

1.6 Time zone handling and DST implications
- Use IANA time zone identifiers (e.g., Europe/London, America/Los_Angeles) to compute local trigger times. Avoid system locale names.
- Two common execution strategies:
  1) Store expressions and evaluate next-run times in UTC: convert cron expression times from local timezone to UTC when scheduling and persist UTC next-run timestamps. Advantage: unambiguous storage; disadvantage: next-run changes around DST.
  2) Evaluate expressions in an IANA time zone at runtime: compute next occurrences using the provided zone so local wall-clock semantics are preserved across DST transitions.
- DST handling rules:
  - Ambiguous local times (clocks set backward): two distinct UTC instants map to same local wall-clock; choose the earlier or later occurrence consistently; document choice.
  - Skipped local times (clocks set forward): some local times do not exist; scheduler must skip or execute at next valid time depending on policy. Recommended default: skip non-existent local times and log as missed runs or schedule next valid instant.
- Use Intl.DateTimeFormat and the IANA registry for validation of time zone identifiers.

1.7 cron-parser (harrisiirak) API: signatures, options, return objects
- Primary function signature:
  parseExpression(expression: string, options?: {
    currentDate?: Date | string,
    endDate?: Date | string,
    iterator?: boolean,
    utc?: boolean,
    tz?: string, // IANA time zone name
    throwException?: boolean,
    useUnixTimestamp?: boolean,
    // Implementation note: some forks support useSeconds: true to allow 6/7-field expressions
  }) => CronIterator | Date
- Return value when iterator option is false:
  next(): Date  // returns next occurrence as JS Date object
  prev(): Date  // returns previous occurrence as JS Date object
  hasNext(): boolean
  // Additional properties:
  fields: {
    seconds?: number[],
    minutes: number[],
    hours: number[],
    dayOfMonth: number[],
    month: number[],
    dayOfWeek: number[],
    years?: number[]
  }
  toString(): string // canonicalized expression
- When iterator option is true, parseExpression returns an iterator whose next() method returns an object {value: Date, done: boolean} (conforms to JS iterator pattern).
- Options effects:
  currentDate sets the base reference instant for computing next/prev occurrences.
  endDate limits generation of occurrences; next() throws or returns done when beyond endDate depending on iterator.
  tz applies IANA time zone rules when computing dates; utc forces UTC semantics.
  iterator toggles iterator output shape.
  throwException toggles whether invalid expressions throw or return a handled error object.

1.8 Parsing/Runtime semantics and edge cases
- Named months/days: map JAN..DEC to 1..12 and SUN..SAT to 0..6 (or 1..7 for Quartz) consistently. Expose mapping table in API docs.
- Steps and ranges validation: "0/15" in minute field interpreted as 0,15,30,45; "5-30/5" interpreted as 5,10,15,20,25,30.
- Leap years and February handling: when DOM contains 29 and month excludes February in non-leap year, skip occurrences for that month.
- End-of-month semantics: when expression refers to 31 and month has fewer days, skip the month occurrence.
- Large backfill or lookahead: when computing next N occurrences, set a maximum attempt limit (e.g., 10,000 iterations) to avoid infinite loops from malformed expressions; return error if limit reached.
- Invalid expression handling: return error with location information (field index, token) if throwException=true; otherwise return a structured error object.

1.9 Concrete examples
- "0 0 * * *" -> every day at 00:00 UTC (or local if tz provided)
- "*/15 9-17 * * MON-FRI" -> every 15 minutes between 09:00 and 17:59 on weekdays
- Quartz: "0 0 12 ? * MON-FRI" -> at 12:00:00 (noon) on every Monday through Friday
- "0 0 0 1 1 ? 2026" (Quartz) -> midnight on January 1, 2026

2. SUPPLEMENTARY DETAILS

2.1 IANA time zone names and validation
- Use full IANA names; validation: test against Intl.supportedValuesOf("timeZone") when available or match against a curated list from IANA TZ database.
- Store time zone identifiers alongside the cron expression and persist them immutably for the schedule; changing the stored identifier should be explicit migration.

2.2 Formatting and presentation (Intl)
- Use Intl.DateTimeFormat(locale, {timeZone: tz, year:'numeric', month:'2-digit', day:'2-digit', hour:'2-digit', minute:'2-digit', second:'2-digit', timeZoneName:'short'}) to render human-readable next-run times in the expression's timezone.

2.3 Best practices
- Persist canonicalized expressions (normalized spacing, upper-cased names, and expanded shorthand replacement) to enable deterministic comparisons.
- Expose two evaluation modes: strict (reject nonstandard extensions) and compatibility (accept vixie or Quartz extensions depending on mode flag).
- Prefer evaluating schedules in the explicit IANA timezone rather than relying on system local time.
- Provide tooling to convert between 5-field cron and 6/7-field Quartz forms with clear documentation of differences.

